Introduction¶

Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania has one of the highest rates of philanthropic dollars per capita in the country, and subsequently has an unusually high rate of nonprofits in the area. Part of the problem identified by folks in the nonprofit sector is that because there are so many, it's hard to find other nonprofits in the city. Sometimes organizations will be doing similar work in different neighborhoods of the city and not even know of each other's existence.

The larger idea behind this project is to eventually be able to visualize where these organizations are based on various demographics of the state, so that we are able to make policy recommendations on where new organizations may be well suitiated, or where there are gaps in services.

This project is a step toward that in which we map the Education, Human Services, and Animal organizations in PA as point data on top of a population chlorepleth map by county. We identify the nonprofits in the state through IRS 990 data that each nonprofit has to submit to the government, find the particular activity codes of the category we are interested in, add the lat/lon coordinates using the Data Science Toolkit, and then finally plot them using the plotly library.

Getting the Data¶

For this demo, we have already gone through the steps needed to have the data frames we need for each category we are looking at for the map, but we will walk through those steps now.

We first create a dictionary of the category codes that the IRS uses. This dictionary will be used in the SQL query we will send the Google BigCloud database, so that we only import those organizations with activity codes that match the category we are interested in. For example, the dictionary would map Human Services to all activity codes that start with 'P'. Later, the API call will go through each nonprofit in the database, compare it to the list of possible activity codes for the user inputted category, and only import those that match.

def createCategoryCodes():
    #creates dictionary of categories (user input -> list of corresponding ntee_codes)
    catCodes = dict(()) 
     
    # Create csv in excel of category activity codes
    with open("activitycodes.csv","r") as allCodes:
         
        # read the CSV into lists
        for entry in allCodes:
            codeList = list()
            codeList = entry.split(',')
            category = codeList[0].upper()
            letter = codeList[1].strip()
            code = letter + (codeList[2]).strip()
             
            # place lists into dictionary depending on if the category key exists or not yet
            if category in catCodes:
                catCodes[category].append(code)
            else:
                catCodes[category] = [code]
     
    # return completed dictionary
    return catCodes

For large datasets, Kaggle has us use Google Cloud BigQuery to access the data. First, we set up the API key and path, then set up the job we need. We have to the execute the parameterized SQL statement that accesses both user inputs - which state the user is interested in, and which category the user is interested in. We import the results of that query into a Pandas data frame.

We then take that data frame and use the Data Science Toolkit API to find the lat/lon coordinates for that nonprofit based on its address, then return that new data frame.

This is the final result that we have saved as CSVs for each of the categories we're looking at for the demo: Education, Human Services, and Animal organizations in PA. (We have commented those commands out so that it doesn't run each time.)

def get_latlondstk(address):
    #uses data science toolkit's api to get lat,lon for a given address
    #if dstk fails, returns 0,0 for lat, lon
    url = "http://www.datasciencetoolkit.org/street2coordinates/" + address
    page = requests.get(url)
    d = page.json()
    if d[address] == None:
        return 0,0
    else:
        lat, lon = d[address]["latitude"], d[address]["longitude"]
        return lat, lon 

def addlatlon(df):
    #adds lat/lon columns to given df, goes through rows and calls get_latlondstk to get lat, lon
    #if 0,0 (get_latlondstk didn't find anything) then drop the row, else put lat/lon into columns
    df["lat"] = np.nan
    df["lon"] = np.nan 
    for i in range(len(df.index)):
        street, city, state, zipcode = df["street"][i], df["city"][i], df["state"][i], df["zip"][i]
        fulladdress = re.sub("\#"," ", street + " " + city + " " + state + " " + zipcode)
        lat, lon = get_latlondstk(fulladdress)
        if (lat,lon) == (0,0):
            df.drop([i], axis = 0, inplace = True)
        else:
            df.loc[i, "lat"] = lat
            df.loc[i, "lon"] = lon
    print(df)
    return df        

def apicall(state,ntee_cd):
    #uses google cloud bigquery api to select nonprofits from the IRS990EIN dataset 
    #using user input of state (default is "PA") and list of ntee codes and returns df
    
    #key path is path to credentials on your own machine - change file path to your own
    key_path = "cf824cf97cfe.json"
    
    credentials = service_account.Credentials.from_service_account_file(
    key_path,
    scopes=["https://www.googleapis.com/auth/cloud-platform"],
    )

    client = bigquery.Client(
            credentials=credentials,
            project=credentials.project_id,
            )
    
    query = """
        SELECT *
        FROM `bigquery-public-data.irs_990.irs_990_ein`
        WHERE state = @state and ntee_cd in UNNEST(@ntee_cd)
    """

    query_params = [
        bigquery.ScalarQueryParameter("state", "STRING", state),
        bigquery.ArrayQueryParameter("ntee_cd", "STRING", ntee_cd),
    ]
    
    query_config = bigquery.QueryJobConfig(query_parameters=query_params)
    
    results = client.query(query, location="US", job_config=query_config)
    
    df = results.to_dataframe()
    print(df)        
    
    #makes sure to close out job after done
    client.cancel_job(results.job_id, location="US")
    
    return df

Then we take these datasets and plot them using plotly. We first create a base map of population density in PA by county, and then create a point map based on each category dataset. You can see the different distributions of these organizations over the same base map of population density.

def load_counties(pacounties):
    #access plotly dataset for county level mapping
    with urlopen('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/plotly/datasets/master/geojson-counties-fips.json') as response:
        #load county information
        counties = json.load(response)
    #separate out pennsylvania counties to a list
    for i in counties["features"]:
        if i['properties']['STATE'] == '42':
            pacounties.append(i)
    #return PA counties 
    return pacounties

def makeaplot(dropdown):
    #create bucket
    pacounties = []
    #load county coordinates & ffip codes
    pa_counties = load_counties(pacounties)
    
    #create fresh dictionary for county
    pa = {}
    pa['type'] = 'FeatureCollection'
    pa['features'] = pa_counties
    
    #FIPS (Federal Information Processing Standards) 
    dffips = pd.DataFrame()
    
    #Read in census data 
    population_data = pd.read_excel(r'2017.pop.county.xlsx')
    
    #Remove first rows
    dffips = pd.DataFrame(population_data['GEO.id2'][1:])
    dfpop = pd.DataFrame(population_data['HC01_VC03'][1:])
    
    
    dffips['pop'] = dfpop[:]
    logs = [math.log(dffips['pop'][i]) for i in range(1, len(dffips['pop']) + 1)]
    pops = [str(dffips['pop'][i]) for i in range(1, len(dffips['pop']) + 1)]
    dffips['poplog'] = logs
    dffips['popstr'] = pops
    dffips = dffips.rename(columns = {'GEO.id2':'fip'})

    
    def maketext_box(text1,text2,text3,text4):
        textbox = []
        for i in range(0,len(text1)):
            text = text1[i]+'<br>'+text2[i] + '<br>' + text3[i] + '<br>' + text4[i]
            textbox.append(text)
        return textbox
    
    def plotit(userchoice):
        lats = dropdown[userchoice]['lat'].tolist()
        lons = dropdown[userchoice]['lon'].tolist()
        text1 = dropdown[userchoice]['name'].tolist()
        text2 = dropdown[userchoice]['street'].tolist()
        text3 = dropdown[userchoice]['citystate'].tolist()
        text4 = dropdown[userchoice]['zipcode'].tolist()
        boxes = maketext_box(text1,text2,text3,text4)
        
        scatt = go.Scattermapbox(lat=lats,
        lon=lons,
        mode='markers+text',
        text=boxes,                
        #hoverinfo='none',                 
        below='',                 
        marker=dict(size=7, color ='rgb(214, 39, 40)', opacity = 0.7))
        
        choro = go.Choroplethmapbox(geojson=pa, locations=dffips['fip'], 
                        z=dffips['poplog'],colorscale="Viridis",colorbar = dict(title = "Population",tickvals = [3,10,16],
                                ticktext = ['<5k', '100k','>1M']), text=dffips['popstr'],zmin=3, zmax=16,
                        marker_opacity=0.5, marker_line_width=0, hoverinfo="text")

        fig = go.Figure(data = [choro,scatt])
        fig.update_layout(mapbox_style="carto-positron",
                          mapbox_zoom=6.5, mapbox_center = {"lat": 41.0033, "lon": -77.6945})
        fig.update_layout(margin={"r":0,"t":0,"l":0,"b":0})
        plotly.offline.iplot(fig)
    
    print("Human Services Organizations")
    plotit('Human Services')
    
    print("Education Organizations")
    plotit('Education')
    
    print("Animal Organizations")
    plotit('Animal')
        
def getpointdata():
    files = ['PA Human Services Orgs.csv', 'PA Education Orgs.csv', 'PA Animal Orgs.csv']
    dropdown = {}
    for file in files:
        locations = {'name':[], 'street':[], 'citystate':[],'zipcode':[], 'lat':[], 'lon':[]}
        with open(file,'r') as f:
            f.readline()
            for line in f:
                place = line.strip().split(',')
                long = place[-1]
                lat = place[-2]
                name = place[2]
                street = place[4]
                city = place[5]
                state = 'PA'
                zipcode = place[7]
                citystate = city + ', ' + state
                locations['name'].append(name)
                locations['street'].append(street)
                locations['citystate'].append(citystate)
                locations['zipcode'].append(zipcode)
                locations['lat'].append(lat)
                locations['lon'].append(long)
        dfpoint = pd.DataFrame(locations)
        keyname = file[3:len(file)-9] 
        dropdown[keyname] = dfpoint
    return dropdown

def main():
    #plot maps
    dropdown = getpointdata()
    makeaplot(dropdown)

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()

Even with just this preliminary level of mapping, we can see some interesting trends - mainly, that regardless of category, most of the nonprofits in PA are clustered around Pittsburgh and Philadelphia, with a scattering of organizations across the more rural portions of the state.

Next Steps for the Project:¶

The next steps for this project would be to create dropdown menus for all of the different categories of nonprofits, including an "all" function so that users would be able to see how the different categories were spread across the state. Another addition could be to add a dropdown menu for which demographics users wanted to see as the base map. A secondary extension would be to make it national and have folks be able to focus on which state they wanted to view as well.
